unittitle.value: Stephen K. Yasinow Collection of Thomas Nast Cartoons

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value:
The Stephen K. Yasinow Collection of Thomas Nast Cartoons contains 71 political cartoons originally featured in 
                <emph render="italic">Harper’s Weekly</emph> magazine between 1863 and 1882.

p.value: Photocopying undertaken by staff only. Limited to twenty exposures of stable, unbound material per day. See guidelines in Print Room for details.
This collection should be cited as: Stephen K. Yasinow Collection of Thomas Nast Cartoons, PR 288, Department of Prints, Photographs, and Architectural Drawings, New-York Historical Society.

Nast moved from Germany to New York in 1846 as a young boy. His professional career began at 15 years of age, when despite having little formal training in drawing, he became an illustrator for
                <emph render="italic">Frank Leslie's Illustrated Weekly</emph>. He later traveled to Italy to report on the Garibaldi campaign for the
                <emph render="italic">Illustrated London News</emph>. Nast began his career at
                <emph render="italic">Harper's Weekly</emph> during the summer of 1862, following the onset of the Civil War. While working at
                <emph render="italic">Harper's Weekly</emph>, he gained a reputation as an outspoken supporter of the Union and the abolition of slavery. Following the Civil War, his work focused largely on exposing corrupt politicians, particularly William M. Tweed, who was arrested in 1872. He left
                <emph render="italic">Harper's Weekly</emph> in 1886 and began serving as consul general in Guayaquil, Ecuador in 1902, where he died of yellow fever.

Subjects to note include: Criticism of William M. Tweed (politician and head of Tammany Hall), Civil War politics and support of the Union Army, post-Civil War politics in America, the use of the donkey and elephant as symbols of the American political parties, and support for Presidents Abraham Lincoln and Ulysses S. Grant. The collection is organized chronologically according to date.
